post_text: Although CUSD has eagerly looked forward to welcoming students back to school for in-person learning on August 12, Stanislaus County school districts were informed today that the current rate of new COVID-19 infections and hospitalizations in our county does not support the safe reopening of schools as hoped. While we are deeply saddened by this news, CUSD is committed to providing an equitable and robust distance learning program for our students until schools are permitted to reopen. Please visit our dedicated Coronavirus webpage http://www.ceres.k12.ca.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=5439732&pageId=48404601 for updates including information shared with families today, or to ask a question for a Frequently Asked Questions page, coming soon.

post_text:
From Superintendent Scott Siegel to CUSD Students, Families and Staff:

There are times when the right words are difficult to find. The circumstances surrounding the deaths of George Floyd, Ahmaud Arbery, Breonna Taylor, and so many others over the years, leading to a wave of national protests over racial inequities and injustices, leave me feeling the need to reach out to all of you. That said, I do not want to voice the usual rhetoric where I state the obvious outrage and promise that we will do better. It is past time for promises. Instead, please read more here https://www.ceres.k12.ca.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=5439732&pageId=48521465 about the concrete steps CUSD has taken to begin down the long path to improve our part of what is so clearly wrong with our society.

This year marks the 50th anniversary of #EarthDay â€“ a day devoted to being kind to our planet. â¤ï¸ğŸŒ Here are 5 activities kids can do:

1âƒ£ Take a nature walk around your neighborhood or yard; see how many birds, trees, or rocks you can count (be sure to practice social distancing).
2âƒ£ Create an art or craft project using recycled materials.
3âƒ£ Plant a seed. No seeds? No problem. Apples, avocados, and peppers all have seeds you can try to grow.
4âƒ£ Color or draw your favorite animal and display your artwork where others can see it on a "safari walk" around your neighborhood.
5âƒ£ Celebrate being kind to the earth by showing kindness to others.

Shared by a CUSD parent: "My daughters LOVE when I receive an alert that their teachers are having a Zoom class. They miss going to school and this allows them to have some kind of normalcy. ... I pray that this pandemic ends soon, but I am so blessed to know my kids' teachers are still communicating with their students."

It is often said that in times of hardship, true character is revealed. We are grateful to be part of an incredible #CUSDfamily of students, parents, staff, and community members who support one another in incredible ways. â¤ï¸ #CeresLearnsAtHome #CUSDaparttogether

post_text:
To help limit the spread of COVID-19 in our community, all schools in the Ceres Unified School District will temporarily close, effective Thursday, March 19 through the end of spring break, Friday, April 17. We recognize that the schools and services operated by the CUSD are vital to families, and that there are likely to be many questions in the coming days and weeks. We will continue to communicate with families through ParentSquare about the resources we are providing to ensure continuity of learning and nutrition for our students, and as new information emerges. Updates and information are also available on our Coronavirus webpage at
http://ow.ly/c9ST50yH9yk. We appreciate the understanding and support of our families, staff, and community during this time. #CeresLearns
